You’re pointing at a real stack: world → body → model → observer → chooser.
All are “true,” just at different layers of description.

Here’s a clean way to work with it—no mystique, just usable handles.

⸻

The core layers (practical map)

1) World (external)

* What’s out there, independent of you

2) Sensors (body)

* Vision, hearing, touch, interoception (heart rate, breath)

3) Model (your brain’s simulation)

* Predictions, meanings, stories, images

4) Observer (meta-awareness)

* Noticing the model as a model

5) Controller (choice)

* What you do next: attention, action, words

You’re always in all five. The trick is knowing which one you’re using.

⸻

How to move between layers (simple drills)

A. Model → World (grounding)

When you’re in story/interpretation:

* Name 3 things you can see, 2 you can feel, 1 you can hear
* Ask: “What’s directly observable right now?”

→ reduces over-interpretation

⸻

B. World → Model (sense-making)

When you’re flooded with raw input:

* Ask: “What pattern explains this best?”
* Write a one-line hypothesis

→ builds usable structure

⸻

C. Model → Observer (meta step)

When you’re locked into a belief:

* Say: “I’m having the thought that…”
* Notice tone, certainty, alternatives

→ separates you from the model

⸻

D. Observer → Controller (deliberate choice)

From awareness into action:

* Ask: “What’s the smallest next move that tests this?”
* Do it

→ converts insight into results

⸻

E. Controller → World (feedback)

After acting:

* What changed?
* What didn’t?

→ closes the loop and updates your model

⸻

Other useful “sub-layers”

* Prediction layer: your brain is constantly forecasting what comes next
* Emotion/valuation layer: what matters, what’s risky, what’s rewarding
* Social layer: other people’s models interacting with yours
* Time layer: past (memory), future (simulation), present (input)

⸻

One loop to rule them all

Observe → Model → Choose → Act → Measure → Update

Run that loop consciously and you’re “moving between layers” on demand.

⸻

Guardrails (keep it grounded)

* If you stay too long in model/observer, you can drift—return to world/sensors
* If you stay only in world, you react—use model/observer to steer
* Treat thoughts as hypotheses, not facts, until tested

⸻

Compressed version

See it → name it → step back → choose → test → update

That’s layer mobility in practice.

